# Prefer PSL examples in design docs

PSL is the default authoring surface (most users come from Prisma 1.x/2.x); the TS contract builder is secondary. Design docs (specs, ADRs, architecture docs, READMEs) should reflect that ordering.

- **Lead with PSL** when illustrating a feature that exists in both surfaces.
- **Use TS only when the content is about the TS surface itself** — model-handle brands, function-form predicates with `ref(modelHandle)`, type-level inference, or any capability PSL's grammar cannot express.
- A TS example that just restates the PSL one is noise — drop it; equivalence is implied.
- Surface-neutral prose should avoid TS-only or PSL-only phrasing where the capability exists in both.

PSL code blocks **must use the `prisma` language tag, never `psl`** — only `prisma` is registered with the highlighters (GitHub, VSCode, docs site); `psl` renders as plain text. (The surface is colloquially "PSL" in prose, but the fence says `prisma`.)

## Why it matters for design

The TS surface is by design a **superset** of PSL: it can express everything PSL can, plus TS-only capabilities (function-form `using`/`withCheck`, richer constraint overrides, closure-scoped helpers). It is never a subset. So **PSL is where the difficult limitations bite** — a static text parser constrains the grammar, and new design pressure surfaces in PSL first. Design a new authoring capability against PSL first; the TS surface follows by mirroring or extending. A design doc that only shows TS also fails to surface the harder design problem.

Runtime code (`db.asUser(jwt)`, `session.sql.from(...)`, middleware, config objects) has no PSL form and stays in TS — this rule covers **authoring** examples (contracts, models, fields, relations, policies), not runtime usage.
